                                <condition>A fragment of an ogham stone reused as building material. Broken off at both ends and also split lengthways. As noted by Macalister (1945, 260) <q>the distal ends of all scores on the H-side have been lost</q>.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris">The inscription along one angle is incomplete at both ends.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The strokes appear to be <rs type="execution" key="chiselled" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/203.html">v-cut</rs>, rather than pocked. The consonant strokes, where they survive in full (on the B side: N and M), are long, narrow and tapering, with the vowel strokes on the angle distinctively shorter. The M stroke is quite evenly spaced between the flanking vowel strokes so that there is no distinctive word division evident.
                                <height><!--letter-heights--></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
